=09
	<div class=3D"entry-content">
	=09








<div class=3D"page_entry">
  <p>
  </p><form name=3D"frmTranslator">
    <p><b>Enter English Text to Translate:</b><br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;
      <textarea name=3D"taEnglish" rows=3D"6" cols=3D"60">Enter the English=
 text here that you want translated into Pig Latin. This is accomplished vi=
a this HTML document and accompanying JavaScript program. Note that hyphena=
ted words are treated as two words. Words may consist of alphabetic charact=
ers only (A-Z and a-z). All punctuation, numerals, symbols and whitespace a=
re not modified.</textarea>
      <br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
      <input type=3D"button" value=3D"Translate">
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
      <input type=3D"button" value=3D"Clear Text">
    </p>
    <p><b>Igpay Atinlay Anslationtray:</b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nb=
sp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Maximum
      Line Length:
      <input type=3D"text" name=3D"txtMaxLength" value=3D"65" size=3D"3" ma=
xlength=3D"2">
      <br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;
      <textarea name=3D"taPigLatin" rows=3D"10" cols=3D"70">The Pig Latin t=
ranslation of the text entered above will
display here when you press the Translate button.

Note:  If the translated text overflows the right margin
of this text box, you may select an alternate Maximum Line
Length above (between 30 and 75 inclusive).
    </textarea>
    </p>
  </form>
 =20



<p>This English to Pig Latin translation program performs a (near-) perfect
    translation of any English text to Pig Latin. Words, phrases, sentences=
,
    paragraphs and more. </p>
  <p>There are many dialects and forms of Pig Latin which vary from region =
to
    region, country to country, and language to language, as well as other =
similar
    Pig Latin-like =E2=80=98languages=E2=80=99. The dialect shown here tend=
s to hail from California/West
    Coast of the United States.</p>
  <p> Basically, the Pig Latin system used here works as follows:<br>
&nbsp;<br>
&nbsp;* Words that start with a vowel (A, E, I, O, U) simply have =E2=80=9C=
WAY=E2=80=9D appended
to the end of the word.<br>
&nbsp;* Words that start with a consonant have all consonant letters up to =
the
first vowel moved<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;to the end of the word (as opposed to just th=
e
first consonant letter), and =E2=80=9CAY=E2=80=9D is appended.<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(=E2=80=98Y=E2=80=99 is counted as a vowel in=
 this context)<br>
&nbsp;<br>
    The algorithm incorporates the following features and special case func=
tionality:
  </p><ul>
    <li> Ensures proper capitalization
    </li><li> Correct upper case and lower case formatting
    </li><li> Correctly translates =E2=80=9Cqu=E2=80=9D (e.g., ietquay inst=
ead of uietqay)
    </li><li> Differentiates between =E2=80=9CY=E2=80=9D as vowel and =E2=
=80=9CY=E2=80=9D as consonant<br>
      (e.g. yellow =3D elloyay and style =3D ylestay) =E2=80=94 (except for=
 a very few exceptions)
    </li><li> Correctly translates contractions
    </li><li> Hyphenated words are treated as two words
    </li><li> Words may consist of alphabetic characters only (A-Z and a-z)
    </li><li> All punctuation, numerals, symbols and whitespace are not mod=
ified
  </li></ul>
  <p></p>
  <p>The routines are written in JavaScript version 1.1 and the algorithms =
were
    developed and programmed by <a href=3D"mailto:donnelly@snowcrest.net">B=
ill
    Donnelly</a>.</p>
  <p> <a href=3D"http://directory.google.com/Top/Science/Social_Sciences/Li=
nguistics/Languages/Constructed/Play/Pig_Latin/">Google
      Web Directory listing for Pig Latin resources<br>
    </a><br>
    <a href=3D"http://www.google.com/intl/xx-piglatin/">Search Google using=
 Pig
    Latin</a> </p></div>
